   "hull": "2D",
   "shields": "",
   "of_note": "No shields, no hyperdrive. The workhorse Imperial starfighter. WEG41010 (AJ#10 Alliance Intelligence Report — TIE Fighters, p.246): The TIE/ln is the third-generation evolution of a starfighter line commissioned in the waning days of the Old Republic. Republic Sienar Systems won the original Twin Ion Engine (T.I.E.) contract because the Old Republic Navy needed a small, fast, inexpensive short-range fighter that fit limited carrier hangar space. When the Empire opted to fund vast Star Destroyer construction over hyperspace-capable starfighters, Sienar (renamed Sienar Fleet Systems) upgraded the basic Imperial TIE into the TIE/ln at roughly one-third the budget of a long-range fighter — and as a side benefit, kept TIE pilots from being able to defect by hyperspace. Strategic profile: TIEs typically operate at 2:1 numerical advantage, supported by TIE/fc fire-control sensor 'painting' and TIE/rc reconnaissance datalinks; their five-stage doctrine (detection, closing, attack, maneuver, disengagement) descends directly from Adar Tallon's Treatise on Starfighter Tactics. Maintenance: under 5% of TIE losses are mundane field attrition, mostly pilot error — sturdy ion engines log more flight hours per fighter than any other Imperial starship, with fewer spares per hour, though spares are difficult to source outside Sienar and licensed shops. Pilots are forbidden personalization but maintain a quietly tolerated tradition: each kill is scored as a one-centimeter mark on the inside of the cockpit hatch; when filled, the hatch is welded above the hangar rack and the TIE is retired with honors and a serial-prefix letter. Wing organization: an Imperial Navy wing is 72 TIEs in six squadrons (3 fighter, 1 recon, 1 interceptor, 1 bomber); an Imperial Army wing is 40 TIEs in 10 flights. Of an Imperial Navy wing, 48 are typically TIE/ln (mixed with 2-4 TIE/fc and 8 TIE/rc), 12 are interceptors, and 0-12 are TIE/gt or TIE bombers. Rebel slang: 'eyeballs' (any TIE/ln), 'breakfast' (TIE element), 'clutch' (flight), 'Emperor's Dozen' (squadron), 'egg basket' (wing), 'eggshells/eggs' (TIEs generally), 'dupes/egglayers' (TIE bombers/gt), 'peepers' (TIE/rc), 'sharps' (TIE/fc), 'squints' (interceptors), 'motherbird' (TIE carrier), 'nest' (TIE garrison). Imperial pilot slang: 'Aurebesh Soup' (Rebel starfighters), 'crosses' (X-wings), 'edges' (A-wings), 'piles' (Y-wings), 'spinners' (B-wings), 'targets' (any ground unit), 'groundhogs' (ground-based pilots, derog.), 'vacheads' (space-based pilots, derog.). Major weakness: the TIE is roughly half as durable as Alliance starfighters, with no shielding (deemed too expensive to retrofit), and its once-famous maneuverability has been out-engineered by newer designs.",
